content:
The sky over London was a canvas of fire. Air raid sirens wailed as bombs fell, turning familiar streets to rubble. In a cramped Anderson shelter, young Thomas clutched his mother’s hand, his father’s uniform photo pressed to his chest.

Across the Channel, on the blood-soaked sand of Normandy, Sergeant Miller fixed his bayonet. Fear was a cold stone in his gut, but the man beside him was trembling more. “Steady, lad,” Miller muttered, his voice lost in the roar of the landing craft ramp dropping. For freedom, they surged forward into the hellish dawn.
